messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
We are at the corner of Riley Thompson and Automobile Road. There's a lady lying in the road. I think she was hit by a car.
Okay, she's got a head injury. Can you confirm the location is Riley Thompson and Automobile Road?
Yes, on Automobile Road, near 4300 Automobile.
Okay, stay on the phone with me. I'm getting help out there. Did you see what happened to her?
We just came upon her. She has a pulse but is unconscious.
Is she breathing?
Yes, she is breathing and has a pulse.
Do you see who hit her or any obvious injuries?
She has a head injury and is lying face down.
Okay, don't move her. Is she by herself?
Yes, she's all alone.
Alright, help is on the way. What's your name?
My name is Mark Klim.
Mark, I got help coming. What's your phone number?
You need to hurry.
They are already on the way. Did anyone see what happened?
No, I'm not sure what else to do. Her pulse is weak.
Okay. Is she halfway in the road?
Yes, but the road is not busy.
What kind of car are you in?
I'm in a burgundy Toyota Camry in the middle of the road.
Do you have your hazard lights on?
Yes.
Does your wife think she needs CPR?
Does she need CPR, Michelle? No, she's still breathing and has a pulse.
Okay. If she needs CPR, I can help with that. The fire department and ambulance are on their way.
Alright, Michelle says she has a pulse, just a weak one.
I need to know if she's breathing normally.
Michelle, is she breathing normally? No, she isn't.
Alright, we need to start CPR. Turn her over carefully, stabilizing her head.
There's another car coming; maybe they can help.
They're on the way. If you can't move her, that's okay, but we need to start CPR if she isn't breathing normally.
Michelle thinks we should move her. She's got a really bad head injury and is bleeding.
Is she bleeding from anywhere specific?
Yes, from her head and her right ear.
Okay, I'm going to check with my supervisor.
We need to turn her over and start CPR. Stabilize her head as you do so.
Got it. Mark, take her hips and shoulders; Michelle will help with her head.
Great. Once she's turned over, check her mouth for any obstructions.
One, two, three. Oh, my God. She isn't breathing.
Start CPR immediately. I'll stay on the phone with you.
Alright, opening her airway now. Michelle, start CPR.
You're doing great. Keep her airway open, and start chest compressions if you can't give breaths.
She's making noises.
That's okay. Keep doing CPR until help arrives.
Where are they?
They're on their way to 4300 Automobile Road. You should hear sirens shortly.
No one else has stopped yet.
You're doing great. It seems long, but they're coming as fast as they can.
We can do this. I can't believe someone hit her and left.
Stay strong. I hear sirens now.
Okay, I hear them too. Keep going, Michelle.
Keep doing CPR until they take over.
He's here now, getting his stuff out.
Alright, let him take over when he's ready.
Thank you. We found her face down.
Mark, what’s your phone number?
My number is [redacted].
You did a great job. Help is there now. I'm going to let you go. Thank you.
Thank you. Bye.
